@TXMCtrades Exchange volume is not 100% correlated to price. Sometimes price goes up a lot more than exchange volume; sometimes exchange volume goes up way more. This happens in other markets too; the Treasury market is way bigger than 10 years ago but volume isn't, so the market cap to volume ratio is skewed greatly. House prices and their total market cap are way more expensive than 3-4 years ago but turnover is super low right now with everyone locked into their mortgages.

But regardless, it's net buy/sell pressure that matters. Price is set on the margin. Every 1% move in bitcoin at current prices is $8 billion in market cap. A 5% daily move is $40 billion in market cap. But it's not because $40 billion flowed in that day; it's because maybe half a billion or one billion did. More buyers than sellers around the margin.

When an entity like $MSTR wants to buy a billion dollars of bitcoin, they purposely split it up into thousands of small transactions spread over days or weeks, because the amount of one-directional value that can and does influence the marginal price is quite small.

